Headlines.Author: Rob Curran
Headlines.Headline: Utilities Down as Forecasters See Mild Summer End -- Utilities Roundup

PARAGRAPH.#text: Shares of power-plant operators declined Tuesday as weather forecasters backed off predictions of a late-summer heatwave, suggesting demand for electricity will soon wane in many U.S. regions. Duke Energy declined after the North Carolina utility said it would jump back into the natural-gas pipeline business, joining three other U.S. energy companies disclosed plans to build the proposed Atlantic Coast Pipeline. Duke would take a 40% stake in the $5 billion pipeline, which is due to transport gas from West Virginia to North Carolina. The other three companies in the joint venture are Dominion Resources, Piedmont Natural Gas and AGL Resources.

Headlines.Headline: Commentary: Zapman's buddy -- Alan Greenspan 11/06-98

PARAGRAPH.#text:
SAN FRANCISCO (CBS.MW) -- A few years ago, I caught Alan Greenspan's Saturday
    morning breakfast speech to a bunch of bankers at a downtown hotel and listened as he
    rambled through his elucidating, albeit somewhat turgid, run-on sentences, which, while
    making Dr. Greenspan one of the nation's most significant orators, in no way -- other than
    those intended by a carefully coordinated public engagement -- effected pertinent
    disclosure of fiscal policy plans, but only deflected the pointed and often self-serving
    questions of the investment community with the sort of pithy obfuscation that has given
    the Fed's chairman a well-deserved and seemingly highly valued reputation for not saying
    very much while he actually explains everything.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Commentary: Zapman's buddy -- Alan Greenspan 11/06-98

Headlines.Headline: Natural gas falls

#text:
NEW YORK (CBS.MW) -- March
    natural gas

fell 5.8 percent Monday as much of the nation enjoyed unseasonably higher
    temperatures. In addition, gas storage levels remain high amid weak U.S.
    demand. On Wednesday, the American Gas Association reported total gas in storage at
    1,599 billion cubic feet, up 7 percent above the average for the last four years. A mild
    winter is cited for the high amount of natural gas in storage. Analysts warn that storage
    level data for the next several weeks may continue to come in below year-ago levels as
    March 1997 was unusually cold. March natural gas fell 13.8 cents to $2.221 per BTU on the
    New York Mercantile Exchange.

#text:
America
    Online

jumped 12 percent on Monday after the nation's largest online service said it's
    raising rates 10 percent for its 11 million customers, and cutting 500 jobs at its
    recently acquired CompuServe unit. Derek Brown, analyst in San Francisco for Volpe Brown
    Whelan & Co., projected the higher rates could add $315 million to revenue and 55
    cents per share in 1999 if the entire $2 flowed to top and bottom lines. Brown said he
    didn't expect that, but saw some of the additional revenue being spent on developing
    content and enhancing service. Indeed, AOL chief executive Stephen Case told analysts not
    to change their numbers; he is slated to meet with the financial community on Thursday in
    New York City.

Headlines.Author: Binti T. Harvey
Headlines.Headline: Chip industry hit by Dataquest report

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Market research firm Dataquest reduced its preliminary fiscal
    1998 growth forecast for the global semiconductor and semiconducor equipment markets
    Monday to take into account Asian economic conditions. Dataquest cut its growth outlook
    for the chip market to 7 percent from 17 percent. The firm said the projection is
    preliminary, and the industry's revenue could fall as low as $160 billion by the end of
    the year. Dataquest's original forecast was for $175 billion in sales. The firm expects
    worldwide chip equipment production to grow by 3 percent, compared to its original
    expectations of 9 percent growth. Dataquest warned its April forecast may be cut further
    if the Korean memory market continues its freefall. Semiconductor
    stocks ended the session lower.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Chip industry hit by Dataquest report

#text:
Investors will have to rethink returns from U.S. stocks this year,
    according to one leading fund manager. "In 1998 we are entering a different investing
    environment than the one we have been in for most of the last 15 years," said
president,

, in an interview
    with Reuters. From 1982 to 1997 returns averaged roughly 19 percent a year. Miller sees
    them dropping to between eight and 10 percent this year. "The strategies needed in
    the new environment are very different" explains Miller, who also manages Legg
    mason's Value
    Fund

. "We love companies that blow up and burn everybody that has owned

HealthCare, under U.S. federal investigation for possible Medicare fraud, which he hopes
